                <td bgcolor="#0A0634" valign="top"
 nowrap><b><font color="#FFFFFF" face="arial" size="2">Balerion</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#0A0634" valign="top"><font color="#FFFFFF" face="arial" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;01/05/2003&nbsp;: 02:42:00 AM</small><hr size="2"><span class="spnMessageText"> QUESTION:  Should I use KEI (Koadics Endless Intellect, the popular level 60 Enchanter mana regen buff) or should I use a Lich line spell(Lick, demi-, arch-, ancient or Seduction of Saryn)?<br /><br />ANSWER:  The general consensus is to stick with Lich line, provided you have acquired appropriate hit point gear.<br /><br />KEI increases mana by 20 per tick, with the added bonus of +25 intelligence/wisdom and +250 to your mana pool (an excellent buff for any casting class).  <br /><br />Lich line is broken down as follows (per tick, etc.):<br /><br />Lich:       +20 mana, -24 hit points<br /><br />Demi Lich:  +31 mana, -48 hit points<br /><br />Arch Lich:  +35 mana, -53 hit points<br /><br />Ancient:    +44 mana, -63 hit points<br /><br />Seduction of Saryn:  +50 mana, -63 hit points<br /><br />Right off the bat, you can see the mana regeneration in the Lich line is equal or better than KEI.<br /><br />Combining a lifetap (i.e. Bond of Death) with a Lich spell, a Necromancer is able to sap health from a target while regenerating mana at a highly increased rate.   <br /><br />KEI tends to cost money and is typically only available in hubs (Nexus, Bazaar, PoK).  Lich line a Necromancer spell, thus readily available.<br /><br />Effectively managing hit points and mana during a battle (whether solo, grouped or raiding) is a core characteristic of the Necromancer class.  Done correctly, a Necromancer will be able to extend the duration of his/her mana supply, often for great lengths of time.<br /><br />"Somebody set us up the bomb."</span></font></td>
              </tr>
